## Yearly transition {#sec-trans}

### Common years {#sec-transc}

The `pently` schedules are important for the transition between years. In common years, the last `dek` of the year (`Dek` `36`) contains the last `pent` of the current year (`Pent` `72`), and the first `pent` of the subsequent year (`Pent` `0`). If these two `pents` follow the default `pently` schedule, `Schedule` `3`, the natural rhythm of 3 workdays followed by 2 rest days continues undisrupted. @tbl-common shows the positive and negative `doties`, names, and types (work or rest) of the days in `Dek` `36` in common years. Notably, while the positive `doties` continue counting past the end of the year, the negative `doties` of the current year turn into the positive `doties` of the subsequent year. The negative `doties` in `Dek` `36` can thus serve as the bridge from the one year to the next.

